</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1436,1801,2032]" lastBlockId="1.[151,1435,152,209]" lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="67" pageId="0" pageNumber="66">
<bibRefCitation author="Grichanov" box="[151,342,1801,1824]" pageId="0" pageNumber="68" refString="Grichanov, I. Ya. (2002) A check list of Swedish Dolichopodidae (Diptera). Entomologisk Tidskrift, 123 (3), 119 - 130." type="journal article" year="2002">
Grichanov (
<number box="[279,335,1801,1824]" pageId="0" pageNumber="66" value="2002.0">2002</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
assigned 
<taxonomicName box="[450,640,1801,1824]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Medetera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="petrophiloides">
<emphasis box="[450,640,1801,1824]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="66">M. petrophiloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName box="[903,1050,1801,1824]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Medetera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="petrophila">
<emphasis box="[903,1050,1801,1824]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="66">M. petrophila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, this is not accepted here and both species can be readily distinguished by a number of characters (e.g., shining vs. pollinose clypeus, colour of propleural bristles and hairs on fore coxae, and some details of the male hypopygium), as 
<bibRefCitation author="Parent" box="[1131,1435,1870,1893]" pageId="0" pageNumber="68" refString="Parent, O. (1938) Faune de France 35 Dipteres Dolichopodides. L'Academie des Sciences de Paris. 720 pp." type="book" year="1938">
Parent (
<number box="[1216,1273,1870,1893]" pageId="0" pageNumber="66" value="1938.0">1938</number>
, figs 
<number box="[1333,1428,1870,1893]" pageId="0" pageNumber="66" value="558.0" valueMax="559.0" valueMin="557.0">557–559</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
has already indicated. Additionally, 
<taxonomicName box="[537,726,1905,1928]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Medetera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="petrophiloides">
<emphasis box="[537,726,1905,1928]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="66">M. petrophiloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has only one strong mesonotal presutural bristle, narrow and long hypopygium (epandrium nearly as long as abdominal segment 
<number box="[832,848,1940,1963]" pageId="0" pageNumber="66" value="4.0">4</number>
), the face with shining median spot; surstyli are about 1.5 times shorter than epandrium but considerably longer than epandrium is broad (
<figureCitation box="[1049,1179,1974,1997]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 – 18" captionStartId="2.[151,270,1185,1209]" captionTargetBox="[158,1420,201,1154]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,194,1162]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 11 – 18. Dorsocentral bristles and male hypopygium, lateral view. 11. M. jacula. 12. M. meridionalis. 13. M. petrophiloides, surstylus. 14, M. petrophiloides. 15. M. petrophila, surstylus. 16. M. petrophila. 17. M. armeniaca, surstylus. 18. M. armeniaca. (from Negrobov &amp; Stackelberg 1972, 1974)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/194407/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="66">
Figs. 
<number box="[1109,1179,1974,1997]" pageId="0" pageNumber="66" value="13.14">13, 14</number>
</figureCitation>
). In 
<taxonomicName box="[1229,1375,1975,1998]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Medetera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="petrophila">
<emphasis box="[1229,1375,1975,1998]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="66">M. petrophila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
there are two dorsocentral presutural mesonotal bristles, the hypopygium is broader, surstyli are short, more than two times as short as the epandrium and shorter than the epandrium is broad (
<figureCitation box="[847,979,152,175]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 – 18" captionStartId="2.[151,270,1185,1209]" captionTargetBox="[158,1420,201,1154]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,194,1162]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 11 – 18. Dorsocentral bristles and male hypopygium, lateral view. 11. M. jacula. 12. M. meridionalis. 13. M. petrophiloides, surstylus. 14, M. petrophiloides. 15. M. petrophila, surstylus. 16. M. petrophila. 17. M. armeniaca, surstylus. 18. M. armeniaca. (from Negrobov &amp; Stackelberg 1972, 1974)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/194407/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="67">
Figs. 
<number box="[908,979,152,175]" pageId="1" pageNumber="67" value="15.16">15, 16</number>
</figureCitation>
). Careful examination of the 
<typeStatus box="[1295,1351,152,175]" pageId="1" pageNumber="67">types</typeStatus>
of both these specimens is required to confirm the proposed validity of these species.
</paragraph>
